Yes, you can generalize the process so that you don't have to repeat the code for every new view. One way to achieve this is by using a Django context processor.

A context processor is a function that adds data to the context of every template rendering. You can create a context processor to include the Google Tag Manager information conditionally based on the production environment. Here's how you can do it:

Step 1: Create a context processor
In your Django project, create a new Python file called `context_processors.py` (or any other name you prefer) within the project directory:

```python
# context_processors.py

from django.conf import settings

def google_tag_manager(request):
    context = {}

    if settings.PRODUCTION_ENVIRONMENT:
        context['google_tag_manager_id'] = 'YOUR_TAG_MANAGER_ID'

    return context
```

In this example, the `google_tag_manager` context processor function checks if the `PRODUCTION_ENVIRONMENT` setting is enabled. If it is, it adds the `google_tag_manager_id` to the context.

Step 2: Register the context processor
In your Django project's settings file (`settings.py`), add the path to your context processor function to the `context_processors` setting. You can add it to the `TEMPLATES` configuration:

```python
# settings.py

# ...

TEMPLATES = [
    {
        # ...
        'OPTIONS': {
            'context_processors': [
                # ...
                'yourproject.context_processors.google_tag_manager',
                # ...
            ],
        },
    },
]

# ...
```

Make sure to replace `'yourproject.context_processors.google_tag_manager'` with the actual path to your context processor function.

Step 3: Use the context variable in templates
In your templates, you can access the `google_tag_manager_id` context variable directly without needing to modify the view functions or classes. For example:

```html
<!-- home.html -->

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Home Page</title>
    <!-- Other meta tags, stylesheets, etc. -->

    {% if google_tag_manager_id %}
        <!-- Google Tag Manager code -->
        <script>
            (function (w, d, s, l, i) {
                w[l] = w[l] || [];
                w[l].push({'gtm.start': new Date().getTime(), event: 'gtm.js'});
                var f = d.getElementsByTagName(s)[0],
                    j = d.createElement(s), dl = l != 'dataLayer' ? '&l=' + l : '';
                j.async = true;
                j.src = 'https://www.googletagmanager.com/gtm.js?id=' + i + dl;
                f.parentNode.insertBefore(j, f);
            })(window, document, 'script', 'dataLayer', '{{ google_tag_manager_id }}');
        </script>
        <!-- End Google Tag Manager code -->
    {% endif %}
</head>
<body>
    <!-- Your page content -->
</body>
</html>
```

By using the context processor, the `google_tag_manager_id` context variable will be available in every template that you render.

Now, you can simply include the Google Tag Manager code snippet in your base template or any other template without worrying about modifying individual view functions or classes.

Note: Don't forget to set the `PRODUCTION_ENVIRONMENT` setting to `True` in your production environment to enable the Google Tag Manager code inclusion.

